An alter ego (Latin, "the other I" or "demonic self" ) is a second self, 
which is believed to be distinct from a person's normal or original 
personality. A person who has an alter ego is said to lead a double life. 
The term appeared in common usage in the early 19th century when 
dissociative identity disorder was first described by psychologists.[1] 
Cicero was the first to coin the term as part of his philosophical 
construct in 1st century Rome, but he described it as "a second self, a 
trusted friend".[2]﻿
